ce:section.ce:para:
The responsivity (Rλ) (the ability of the device to generate the photocurrent to the incident UV light) is determined by Rλ = JPh/PUV, where JPh(JUV - JDark) is photocurrent density and PUV is the power (1 mW/cm2) of UV light illumination [60,61]. The pristine ZnO thin film-based device A revealed the linear increase in the responsivity (Rλ) [35.2/33 (+8/−8 V), 12/11 (+3/−3 V), and 4.5/4.2 mA/W (+1/−1 V)] upon increasing the bias voltages (both positive and negative), showing the efficient generation and transport of charge carriers of sol-gel derived spin-coated ZnO thin film [as shown in Fig. 7
                        (i)]. The important parameter of the photodetector to indicate the ability to generate the number of electrons per incident photon is given by the external quantum efficiency (EQE) (η) which is determined by using the equation of η = (R x hc/λ) x 100%, where λ is the wavelength (365 nm) of incident UV light [60,61]. Device A exhibited the higher EQE (η) of 12/11.1 (at +8/−8 V), 4.1/3.7 (+3/−3 V), and 1.5/1.4% (+1/−1 V) [Fig. 7(ii)]. The detectivity (Dλ) is another important quantity (figure of merit) to characterize the photodetector for its ability to detect the incident photon, determined by using the relation of Dλ = R/√(2qJDark), where q is the charge of the electron and Dλ is measured in Jones. It is found to be 3.3/2.1 (at +8/−8 V), 1.7/1.4 (+3/−3 V), and 0.9/0.9 × 1011 Jones (+1/−1 V) for the pristine ZnO film in the reference Device A (Fig. 8
                        ).
